problems.title: Rotate Array by K Steps (Right Rotation)
problems.description:
Problem Statement
You are given an array of N integers and an integer K. Your task is to rotate the array to the right by K steps. After rotation, each element shifts to the right K times, and the last K elements move to the front.

Note: If K is greater than N, take K = K % N.

Time Complexity
The optimal solution uses reverse operations with O(N) time and O(1) space.
Brute force approach may take O(N*K).

Input Format
The first line contains an integer N (size of the array).
The second line contains N space-separated integers.
The third line contains integer K.

Output Format
Print the rotated array elements after K right rotations.

Explanation Example
Input:
7
1 2 3 4 5 6 7
3
Rotate 3 steps right -> [5 6 7 1 2 3 4]
Output: 5 6 7 1 2 3 4
problems.constraints:
1 ≤ N ≤ 100000
1 ≤ K ≤ 100000
Values may be negative or positive
Expected time complexity: O(N)

problems.title: Rotate Array by K Steps (Left Rotation)
problems.description:
Problem Statement
You are given an array of N integers and an integer K. Your task is to rotate the array to the left by K steps. After rotation, each element shifts to the left K times, and the first K elements move to the end.

Note: If K is greater than N, use K = K % N.

Time Complexity
The optimal method uses reverse operations with O(N) time and O(1) space.
The brute force approach shifting each element K times takes O(N*K).

Input Format
The first line contains an integer N (size of the array).
The second line contains N space-separated integers.
The third line contains integer K.

Output Format
Print the rotated array elements after K left rotations.

Explanation Example
Input:
7
1 2 3 4 5 6 7
3
Rotate left by 3 steps -> [4 5 6 7 1 2 3]
Output: 4 5 6 7 1 2 3
problems.constraints:
1 ≤ N ≤ 100000
1 ≤ K ≤ 100000
Values may be negative or positive
Expected time complexity: O(N)

problems.title: Find All Distinct Pairs with Target Sum
problems.description:
Problem Statement
You are given an array of N integers and an integer K. Your task is to find all distinct pairs (a, b) such that a + b = K. Each pair must be printed in sorted order (a < b) and overall result must also be printed in ascending order based on the first value.
If no such pair exists, print -1.

Distinct Pair Rule
If a number repeats, use it only once per unique pair. Example: In [1,1,2,2] with K=3 → pairs: (1,2)

Time Complexity
Brute force approach takes O(N^2).
Optimized using sorting + two pointers in O(N log N).
Space complexity: O(1).

Input Format
The first line contains an integer N.
The second line contains N space-separated integers.
The third line contains integer K.

Output Format
Print all distinct pairs in format "a b" each on a new line.
If no pairs exist, print -1.

Example
Input:
6
1 5 7 -1 5 3
6
Output:
1 5
3 3
Explanation: Unique pairs whose sum = 6 are (1,5) and (3,3).
problems.constraints:
1 ≤ N ≤ 100000
Values may be negative or positive
Expected Time Complexity: O(N log N)

problems.title: Check if Pair Sum Exists using Sorting
problems.description:
Problem Statement
You are given an array of N integers and an integer K. Your task is to check if there exists a pair of numbers in the array whose sum is equal to K, using a sorting-based approach.
If such a pair exists, print YES. Otherwise, print NO.

Approach
1. Sort the array.
2. Use two pointers (left = 0, right = N-1).
3. If arr[left] + arr[right] == K → pair found.
4. If sum < K → move left pointer.
5. If sum > K → move right pointer.

Time Complexity
Sorting takes O(N log N), Two-pointer traversal takes O(N). Total complexity: O(N log N).
Space Complexity: O(1).

Input Format
The first line contains an integer N.
The second line contains N space-separated integers.
The third line contains integer K.

Output Format
Print YES if any pair sum equals K, else NO.

Example
Input:
6
1 4 45 6 10 -8
16
Possible pairs: (6, 10). So output is YES.
problems.constraints:
1 ≤ N ≤ 100000
Values may be negative or positive
Expected Time Complexity: O(N log N)

problems.title: Remove All Duplicates from Array (Keep Unique)
problems.description:
Problem Statement
You are given an array of N integers. Your task is to remove all elements that appear more than once and keep only unique elements.
Print the resulting array in the same order as original. If no unique elements remain, print -1.

Example: For input [1 2 2 3 4 4 5], the unique elements are [1, 3, 5].

Time Complexity
The optimal solution uses hashing to count frequencies in O(N) time and O(N) extra space.

Input Format
The first line contains an integer N (size of array).
The second line contains N space-separated integers.

Output Format
Print unique elements separated by space.
If no unique elements exist, print -1.

Explanation Example
Input:
7
1 2 2 3 4 4 5
Output:
1 3 5
Because 2 and 4 appear multiple times, so they are removed entirely.
problems.constraints:
1 ≤ N ≤ 100000
Values may be negative or positive
Expected Time Complexity: O(N)
